{{Infobox protein family | Symbol = KCNQC3-Ank-G_bd | Name = Ankyrin-G binding motif of KCNQ2-3 | image = | width = | caption = | Pfam = PF11956 | Pfam_clan = | InterPro = IPR020969 | SMART = | PROSITE = | MEROPS = | SCOP = | TCDB = | OPM family = | OPM protein = | CAZy = | CDD = }} In molecular biology, the '''ankyrin-G binding motif of KCNQ2-3''' is a [[protein motif]] found in the [[potassium channels]] [[KvLQT2|KCNQ2]] and [[KvLQT3|KCNQ3]].
Interactions with ankyrin-G ([[ANK3|ankyrin-3]]) are crucial to the localisation of [[Voltage-gated channel|voltage-gated]] [[sodium channels]] (VGSCs) at the [[axon]] initial segment and for [[neurons]] to initiate [[action potential]]s. This [[conserved sequence|conserved]] 9-[[amino acid]] [[protein motif|motif]] (([[Valine|V]]/[[Alanine|A]])[[Proline|P]]([[Isoleucine|I]]/[[Leucine|L]])AXX[[Glutamic acid|E]]([[Serine|S]]/[[Aspartic acid|D]])D) is required for ankyrin-G binding and functions to localise sodium channels to a variety of 'excitable' [[Cell membrane|membrane]] domains both inside and outside of the [[nervous system]].<ref name="pmid12716895">{{cite journal |vauthors=Lemaillet G, Walker B, Lambert S | title = Identification of a conserved ankyrin-binding motif in the family of sodium channel alpha subunits | journal = J. Biol. Chem. | volume = 278 | issue = 30 | pages = 27333–9 |date=July 2003 | pmid = 12716895 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.M303327200 | url = }}</ref> This motif has also been identified in the [[potassium channel]] 6[[transmembrane|TM]] [[protein]]s KCNQ2 and KCNQ3 <ref name="pmid16525039">{{cite journal |vauthors=Pan Z, Kao T, Horvath Z, Lemos J, Sul JY, Cranstoun SD, Bennett V, Scherer SS, Cooper EC | title = A common ankyrin-G-based mechanism retains KCNQ and NaV channels at electrically active domains of the axon | journal = J. Neurosci. | volume = 26 | issue = 10 | pages = 2599–613 |date=March 2006 | pmid = 16525039 | doi = 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.4314-05.2006 | url = }}</ref> that correspond to the M channels that exert a crucial influence over [[neuronal]] excitability. KCNQ2/KCNQ3 channels are preferentially localised to the surface of axons both at the axonal initial segment and more [[distally]], and this axonal initial segment targeting of surface KCNQ channels is mediated by these ankyrin-G binding motifs of KCNQ2 and KCNQ3.<ref name="pmid16735477">{{cite journal |vauthors=Chung HJ, Jan YN, Jan LY | title = Polarized axonal surface expression of neuronal KCNQ channels is mediated by multiple signals in the KCNQ2 and KCNQ3 C-terminal domains | journal = Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | volume = 103 | issue = 23 | pages = 8870–5 |date=June 2006 | pmid = 16735477 | pmc = 1472242 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0603376103 | url = }}</ref> KCNQ3 is a major determinant of M channel localisation to the AIS, rather than KCNQ2.<ref name="pmid17311847">{{cite journal |vauthors=Rasmussen HB, Frøkjaer-Jensen C, Jensen CS, Jensen HS, Jørgensen NK, Misonou H, Trimmer JS, Olesen SP, Schmitt N | title = Requirement of subunit co-assembly and ankyrin-G for M-channel localization at the axon initial segment | journal = J. Cell Sci. | volume = 120 | issue = Pt 6 | pages = 953–63 |date=March 2007 | pmid = 17311847 | doi = 10.1242/jcs.03396 | url = }}</ref> [[Phylogenetic]] analysis reveals that anchor motifs [[evolution|evolved]] sequentially in [[chordates]] (NaV channel) and jawed [[vertebrates]] (KCNQ2/3).<ref name="pmid19112491">{{cite journal |vauthors=Hill AS, Nishino A, Nakajo K, Zhang G, Fineman JR, Selzer ME, Okamura Y, Cooper EC | title = Ion channel clustering at the axon initial segment and node of Ranvier evolved sequentially in early chordates | journal = PLoS Genet. | volume = 4 | issue = 12 | pages = e1000317 |date=December 2008 | pmid = 19112491 | pmc = 2597720 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pgen.1000317 | url = }}</ref>
